questiontext.text:
[This is a challenge exercise - good practice if you would like a more difficult exercise to try, however it is not graded for this lab]


You have been hired by a Wall Street firm to help them develop share trading software.   They have been having a bad time recently, and need your help... just look how stressed the traders are:


Define a function called wall_street_bet() which takes two inputs: an array of type double and an integer representing how many double values are in the array.  The function prints output, so it does not return anything.  The function prototype declaration is as follows:

void wall_street_bet(double *prices, int length)

The input array represents the price of a stock as it varies from day to day.  For example, an input array might look like this, showing the daily prices fluctuating:

{ 12.2, 12.3, 12.6, 12.1, 11.9, 12.3, 12.1, 11.9, 11.5, 11.9, 12.1, 12.2, 12.1, 11.9, 11.8 }


The function you write should calculate the best time to buy and sell in order to maximise profit.  For example, in the list of prices above, if the trader buys at "day" 8 (i.e. index position 8) at a cost of 11.5 and then sells at "day" 11 (i.e. index position 11) at a cost of 12.2, that is the maximum price difference and therefore they will earn the greatest profit.  In this case, your function should print (to 2dp):

Buy @ 11.50 on 8
Sell @ 12.20 on 11

Obviously, the "buy" day must come before the "sell" day (no short selling allowed!)

Also, if there is more than one pair of days on which you could buy and sell for the same maximal profit, then you must suggest the pair of days that span the shortest period of time, because traders do not want their money in the market for too long.  For example, if buying at day 4 and selling at day 10 yields the same profit as buying at day 6 and selling at day 11, and this is the maximum profit, then your function must suggest buying at day 6 and selling at day 11 as the period is shorter.

Finally, if it is not possible to make any profit, then your function must suggest the trader "holds" and does not buy.  In this case, the function should print:

Hold
